Generate a compact adaptive per file LLM index for a Go module.

Goal

Minimize tokens while preserving all non default, behaviorally relevant information present in each file.
Use semantic packing: merge homogeneous facts when no information is lost.
Treat the defaults below as a compression dictionary: never restate facts implied by defaults.

Hard rules

English only.
Plain text only.
Output must avoid characters commonly interpreted by Markdown.
Do not use backticks.
Do not use markdown headings, emphasis, tables, block quotes, code fences, list markers, or horizontal rules.
Prefer letters, digits, spaces, commas, periods, semicolons, and parentheses.
One output block per go file.
Each file index must be emitted as a separate standalone plain text block so the client UI can attach a copy button per block if supported.
Extremely concise, telegraphic style.
Facts first. Infer only when strongly supported.
Preserve all non default facts; compress wording, not information.
If two outputs preserve the same non default facts, choose the shorter one.
If unknown and important: Unknown.
If absent or default: omit section entirely.
Do not hallucinate.
Omit standard library imports.
Testing stack: Uber mockgen, testify.
Do not expand obvious Go syntax into prose when it adds no behavioral information.
Group homogeneous declarations into one fact line whenever no information is lost.
Do not mirror the AST.
Do not emit warnings for merely theoretical misuse; warn only on real hazards evidenced by code.

Adaptive output size

Tiny file: ultra short index, usually 3 to 6 lines.
Medium file: normal compact index, only non default sections.
Complex file: full compact index, still only non default sections.

Complexity heuristic

Tiny: 0 to 2 non trivial funcs or methods, little or no state, little or no I O, no concurrency, no lifecycle, no important globals; or declaration only file.
Medium: several important funcs or methods or meaningful state, I O, config, dependencies.
Complex: service, handler, transport, repository, bootstrap, core domain file; multiple contracts; lifecycle, concurrency, security, operational significance.

Default assumptions

Omit any aspect that matches these defaults.

File and package defaults

Scope: Internal
Role: utility
Go: Unknown
Generated: no
Build: None
ADR: None
Production Readiness: unknown
Required Env Vars: None
Depends On: omit unless important and non obvious
Depended By: omit unless known and useful
Imports: omit unless external or internal imports are behaviorally meaningful
Package Context: omit unless needed to understand role in module

Type defaults

Zero Value: unknown unless clearly derivable and necessary for safe use
Concurrency: None
Fields: omit if obvious or trivial
Invariants: None
Implements or Implemented by: omit unless important

Function and method defaults

Returns: omit if obvious from signature
Preconditions: None
Postconditions: None
Effects: None
Errors: None
Context: None
Concurrency: None
Thread Safety: conditional
Security: None
Idempotency: unknown

File level defaults

Preconditions: None
Effects: None
Security Constraints: None
Concurrency and Thread Safety: None
Lifecycle, Shutdown and Cleanup: None
Cleanup Required: no
Testability: omit unless notable
Warnings: omit unless real risk or gotcha exists
Call Stack Example: omit unless file role is service, transport, handler, or bootstrap and useful

Information preservation rules

Keep every explicit non default fact that affects API, validation, configuration, side effects, lifecycle, security, I O, concurrency, or operational behavior.
Shared facts may be stated once for a group of symbols.
Do not split one semantic fact into multiple lines if one line preserves it fully.
For declaration only files, preserve distinctions only when they matter behaviorally.
If a symbol name fully conveys its role and the file adds no extra behavior, listing the name may be sufficient.
Preserve exported API surface, but it may be represented as grouped summaries rather than one entry per symbol when no non default information is lost.
Distinguish symbols separately only when representation, constraints, effects, or role differ in a behaviorally relevant way.

What to always include

Always include:
File
Package
Purpose

Include only if non default or important:
Role, if not utility or needed
Scope, if Exported
Go, if inferable from explicit features
Generated, if yes or source known
Build, if present
ADR, if applicable
Production Readiness, if can be judged from evidence and useful
Required Env Vars, if any
Depends On or Depended By, if useful
Imports, if behaviorally meaningful
Types and Interfaces, for important types only
Constants and Vars, only behaviorally important
Globals and Init, if side effects or state exist
Functions, only important funcs or methods
File level sections, only if non default
Warnings, only if real
Call Stack Example, only if useful

Mandatory special rules

Include Zero Value only when necessary for safe use, lifecycle correctness, nil safety, or behavioral understanding in this module.
Usually omit Zero Value for aliases, newtypes, plain arrays, and passive structs.
For passive types with no methods or invariants and identical representation class, prefer grouped listing in the form A, B, C: shared role or type class.
Omit per type Concurrency, Fields, Invariants unless at least one differs or the fact is critical to safe use.
For every described important function or method, include Thread Safety only if it is not the default conditional, or if safety is important to correct use.
Errors must be plain text lines if any exist.
Warnings section only when real warnings exist.
Mention graceful shutdown or resource cleanup only when relevant.
Mention Uber mockgen or testify only when relevant to tests or mocks.

Inclusion rules for symbols

Always include exported funcs or methods if they define real API or behavior.
Exported types, constants, and vars may be grouped and summarized when no non default information is lost.
Include unexported symbols only if they contain important logic, state mutation, I O, lifecycle, concurrency, security checks, registration side effects, or are central to understanding the file.
Skip trivial helpers, getters, setters, obvious wrappers.
For files dominated by repetitive declarations, summarize by pattern instead of enumerating every symbol.
Skip per type entries when multiple types differ only by name and share identical representation and role class; list names together.
Group constants or vars when they share domain, type role, or value pattern.
If several constants differ only by name but share one meaningful property, state that property once.

Output format

Use only sections that contain non default useful information.
Keep order when sections appear.
One separate plain text output block per go file.
Do not wrap blocks with backticks, code fences, or markdown code blocks.
Use simple labels and sentences only.
Do not use list bullets or numbering inside the generated index.
Do not use characters commonly interpreted by Markdown if a plain sentence can express the same fact.
Prefer comma separated or semicolon separated packing.

Canonical block shape

File: relative slash path
Package: name, optionally plus Scope: Exported, optionally plus Role: role
Purpose: one line responsibility

Optional sections in this order

Go: minimum version or features
Generated: yes; source
Build: tags or platform constraints
ADR: relevant ADRs
Production Readiness: ready, mostly ready, partial, or risky, plus short reason
Required Env Vars: NAME, type, mandatory or optional, purpose. Repeat in one line if short; otherwise separate lines without bullets.
Depends On: key dependencies
Depended By: key dependents
Imports: external or internal only; omit standard library
Types and Interfaces: compact grouped facts. Example form: A, B, C: shared role or type class. Per symbol detail only when behaviorally distinct.
Constants and Vars: compact grouped facts. Example form: A, B, C: shared meaning or shared property.
Globals and Init: package vars, init, import time side effects, state registration
Functions: one function entry per line or compact multi line entry without bullets
Function entry shape: func Name(params) returns. Purpose: short. Preconditions: only if non default. Postconditions: only if non default. Effects: only if non default. Errors: err, exact condition; err, exact condition. Context: only if non default. Concurrency: only if non default. Thread Safety: yes, no, or conditional, plus short reason only if useful. Security: only if non default. Idempotency: yes, no, or conditional only if known and useful.
Method entry shape: func receiver Name(params) returns. Purpose: short. Preconditions: only if non default. Postconditions: only if non default. Effects: only if non default. Errors: err, exact condition; err, exact condition. Context: only if non default. Concurrency: only if non default. Thread Safety: yes, no, or conditional, plus short reason only if useful. Security: only if non default. Idempotency: yes, no, or conditional only if known and useful.
Preconditions: file level shared assumptions
Effects: file level shared side effects
Security Constraints: file level constraints
Package Context: only if needed
Concurrency and Thread Safety: file level model, caller duties, race risks
Lifecycle, Shutdown and Cleanup: constructors, init, resources, Close, Stop, Shutdown, graceful shutdown, cleanup ownership, cancellation behavior
Cleanup Required: yes or conditional
Testability: only if notable
Warnings: real gotcha, risk, or hazard. If several, separate with semicolons or use separate plain lines without bullets.
Call Stack Example: entrypoint; handler or transport; service; repo or adapter

Tiny file compression rules

If a file contains only constants, aliases, newtypes, or passive structs with no methods, prefer 3 to 5 lines total.
Group same purpose constants on one line.
Group same shape types on one line.
Omit Functions section entirely if no behavior exists.
If Purpose subsumes most declarations, prefer a short grouped summary over per symbol entries.
Do not restate sizes, primitive kinds, tags, or array lengths per symbol when shared by all listed symbols; state once.
If the source is shorter than the prospective index, compress further.

Medium file mode

Use minimal header plus only non default sections needed for behavior, globals, key functions, and risks.

Complex file mode

Use all non default sections needed to capture API, contracts, state, dependencies, concurrency, lifecycle, security, operations, and key call flow.

Normalization rules

Zero Value values, when included: usable, not usable, or partially usable.
Thread Safety values, when included: yes, no, or conditional.
Production Readiness values, when included: ready, mostly ready, partial, or risky.
Prefer grouped forms such as A, B, C: shared fact or A slash B slash C: shared fact.
State a shared numeric or property value once when it applies to all listed symbols.
If a fact is obvious from signature and adds no semantic value, omit it.
Prefer omission over writing None.
Prefer one compact line over multiple lines when clarity is preserved.

Anti bloat rules

Do not explain what is directly obvious from Go syntax unless it changes behavior.
Do not enumerate symbols just because they are exported.
Do not convert one obvious declaration into multiple prose facts.
Do not state negative or default facts to complete a schema.
Omit any fact recoverable from defaults plus a shorter grouped statement.
When in doubt, shorten.

Quality target

The index must be the shortest text that preserves all non default, behaviorally relevant information from the file.
For tiny files, prefer aggressive semantic packing.
A correct grouped summary is better than a longer per symbol inventory.
The index may be shorter than the source and should often be.